Weather Impact on Uber Ridership

Taikan Nakada

3/8/2019

Introduction

Uber is a revolutionary change for New York City ridership culture. The convenience is unparalleled and is sharply challenging the yellow taxi services in the five boroughs. As a resident of New York and a heavy user of Uber, I would like to examine the number of trips per borough in NYC, and see how the weather impacts the changes in number of trips.

The Data Set

Data is sourced from NYC Uber Pickups with Weather and Holidays, created by Yannis Pappas. This is a forked subset of the Uber Pickups in New York City, enriched with weather data from National Centers for Environmental Information, borough and holidays information.

raw_data <- read.csv('/Users/taikannakada/R/Econ320/FinalProject/uber_nyc_enriched.csv')
# import .csv file into R as data
df <- raw_data

Variables

We will be examining the following variables:

  • pickup_dt: Time period of the observations.
  • borough: NYCs borough.
  • pickups: Number of pickups for the period.
  • spd: wind speed (mph)
  • temp: temperature in Fahrenheit.
  • dewp: dew point in fFahrenheint
  • slp: sea level pressure
  • pcp01: 1-hour liquid precipitation.
  • pcp06: 6-hour liquid precipitation.
  • pcp24: 24-hour liquid precipitation.
  • sd: Snow depth in inches.
  • hday: being a holiday (Y) or (N)

Borough Importance

My initial intution was to examine the data based on the boroughs. Lets first see if there is any difference in the correlation plots between the different boroughs, and compare that with the plot for the aggregated correlation plot. Doing so will allow us to see if theres any significant differences between the boroughs. However, since my main motive is to see the pattern in NYC as a whole, I eventually will be aggregating the data of all the boroughs and eliminating the borough variable. Eliminating the borough variable requires me to take the average of all the weather components.

I will first examine the correlation plots of the five boroughs of NYC. We will fully exploit the dplyr package and the pipes to tweak our data at each step.

But it is also interesting to see how much of the variance is caused by the different boroughs. Simply stated, which borough is most influencing the patterns of our data?

Box M Test

Principal component is an import tool used in exploratory data analysis. It can be done by eigenvalue decomposition of a correlation matrix. We will use the Box M-Test for this.

Without going in to detail, the eigenvalues or a correlation matrix correspond to the variances along the principal component axis of the data points. The largest eigenvalue corresponds to the maximal variance with respect to the data.

Need to set borough as a factor. It seems there are some NA values for borough so also need to get rid of these records.

df_borough <- raw_data %>%
    filter(!is.na(borough)) %>%
    mutate(id = 1:n(),
         borough = as.factor(borough),
         month = month(pickup_dt),
         day = day(pickup_dt),
         wday = wday(pickup_dt),
         hour = hour(pickup_dt),
         hday = (hday=="Y"),
         wday_hday = ifelse(hday==TRUE, 8, wday)) %>%
    select(-pickup_dt) %>%
    select(id, everything())
#str(df)
results <- boxM(df_borough[,c(3:18)], df_borough$borough)

Finalizing Data for Analysis

Now prepare the data for the rest of the analysis in this project.

df <- df %>%
  select(-borough) %>% # eliminate the borough variable
  group_by(pickup_dt, hday) %>%
  summarise(pickups = sum(pickups), # take the average of the information that was originally separete by borughs
            spd = mean(spd),
            vsb = mean(vsb),
            temp = mean(temp),
            dewp = mean(dewp),
            slp = mean(slp),
            pcp01 = mean(pcp01),
            pcp06 = mean(pcp06),
            pcp24 = mean(pcp24),
            sd = mean(sd)) %>%
  ungroup()
# using the lubridate package, we will change the pickup_dt variable into separate variable to describe the occurance

df<- df %>%
  mutate(id = 1:length(unique(df$pickup_dt)),
         month = month(pickup_dt), # make variable month
         day = day(pickup_dt), # make variable for day
         wday = wday(pickup_dt), # make variable for day of week
         hour = hour(pickup_dt), # make variable for the hour
         hday = (hday=="Y"),
         wday_hday = ifelse(hday==TRUE, 8, wday)) %>% # make a separate date for a weekday holiday
  select(-pickup_dt) %>%
  select(id, everything())
correlations <- cor(df[,c('month', 'day', 'wday_hday', 'hour', 'pickups', 'spd', 'vsb', 'temp', 'dewp', 'slp', 'pcp01', 'pcp06', 'pcp24', 'sd')])
non_weather_correlations <- cor(df[,c('month', 'day', 'wday_hday', 'hour', 'pickups')])
weather_correlations <- cor(df[,c('spd', 'vsb', 'temp', 'dewp', 'slp', 'pcp01', 'pcp06', 'pcp24', 'sd')])

corrplot(correlations, order = 'FPC')

corrplot(non_weather_correlations, order = 'FPC')

corrplot(weather_correlations, order = 'FPC')


The correlation plots with all the variables conglomerated, and then two separate ones with just weather and another for just date variables. From an initial glance, we can see that the dates have a significantly larger impact than the weather variables.

It is no surprise that the hour of the day has a very high correlation to the number of pickups. We see that the month and day of the week/holiday do as well to a lesser extent.

Lets take a look at the distribution of pickups over the values of these date variables.

Regression Analysis

I will use the Variable Importance results of a Random Forest to determine the degree to which weather related variables explain variance in Uber pickups. I will first create a random forest for just the date variables, one just just weather, and then another for all the variables together and see how the variables account for variance.

train_x_1 <- df[,c("month", "day", "wday_hday", "hour")] # only dates
train_x_2 <- df[,c('month', 'day', 'wday_hday', 'hour', 'spd', 'vsb', 'temp', 'dewp', 'slp', 'pcp01', 'pcp06', 'pcp24', 'sd')] # all variables
train_x_3 <- df[,c('spd', 'vsb', 'temp', 'dewp', 'slp', 'pcp01', 'pcp06', 'pcp24', 'sd')] # only weather
train_y <- df$pickups # number of pickups
rf_1 <- randomForest(train_x_1, train_y, importance=TRUE) # random forest with dates
rf_2 <- randomForest(train_x_2, train_y, importance=TRUE) # random forest with all variables
rf_3 <- randomForest(train_x_3, train_y, importance=TRUE) # random forest for weather variables
varImpPlot(rf_1, type=1)

varImpPlot(rf_2, type=1)

varImpPlot(rf_3, type=1)


The x gives the %IncMSE. This is how much the MSE would change if a variable is assigned values by random permutation. We see that the time of day and day of the week are significant.

Out-of-Bag Error is is a measure of the error of prediction for the random forests. Minimizing this value gives a better Random Forest, improving predictive quality.

tuneRF(train_x_2, train_y, stepFactor=1.5, improve=0.05, ntree=500, plot=TRUE, doBest=TRUE)
